[{"id":"VR733032","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR733021.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">In the last line of the poem, the use of the word “Here” mainly serves to</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR733032_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<p class=\"introduction passage-intro\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Read the following poem carefully before you choose your answers.</span></p>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">Simon Ortiz’ poem “Making Quiltwork” was published in 2002.</span></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"poetry style:1\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p class=\"title_line passage-title\">Making Quiltwork</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"verse\"><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>Like the coat of many colors,<span class=\"footnote\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"footnote_mark\">1</span><span class=\"footnote_text\">In the Bible, the “coat of many colors” is a garment given to Joseph by his father Jacob as a sign of his favor.</span></span> the letters, scraps,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>all those odds and bits we live by, we have come</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>to know. Folks here live by the pretty quilts</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>they make, more than make actually, more than pretty.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">5</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>They are histories, their lives and their quilts.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>Indian people who have been scattered, sundered</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>into odds and bits, determined to remake whole cloth.</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>Nothing quits. It changes many times, sometimes</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>to something we don't want, but we again gather</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">10</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>the pieces, study them, decide, make decisions again,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>yes, and fit them to color, necessity, conditions,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>taste and choice, and start again. Our lives are quilts,</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>letters, odds and bits, scraps, but always the thread</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>loving through them, the compassionate knowledge</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">15</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>that what we make is worth it and will outlast</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>anything that was before and will be worthy</span><br />\n<span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>of any people's art, endeavor, and final triumph.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"verse\"><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"line_number badge badge-inverse\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"indent indent_0\"></span>Here, look at my clothes, quilts, coats of many colors!</span></div>\n<span class=\"mandatory_credit_block\"><span style=\"font-size:0.8em;\"><span class=\"mandatory_credit_line\">From <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">Out There Somewhere</span> by Simon J. Ortiz. © 2002 Simon J. Ortiz. Reprinted by permission of the University of Arizona Press.</span></span></span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">create a sense of immediacy for the reader</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">underscore the speaker’s wry self-awareness</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">indicate the speaker’s offer of a gift to an unnamed addressee</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">reinforce the speaker’s attempt to recapture a memory</p>"],"answer":1}]